<paragraph id="E8403669FF80FFFCFF591B5386F0B02E" blockId="23.[160,1155,350,549]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">
Adults are small, agile, fast, and bright orange-red. We regularly found 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF80FFFCFC6B1B538109B37C" box="[1010,1117,350,375]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Perithemis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="domita">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF80FFFCFC6B1B538153B37C" box="[1010,1031,350,375]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">P.</emphasis>
<materialsCitation id="58973C34FF80FFFCFB961B538109B37C" box="[1039,1117,350,375]" location="St" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" specimenCount="1">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF80FFFCFB961B538109B37C" box="[1039,1117,350,375]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">domita</emphasis>
</materialsCitation>
</taxonomicName>
on 
<location id="ED2060B2FF80FFFCFF391B8C85EDB391" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:6056877FFF80FFFCFE5D1B2486F0B02E:ED2060B2FF80FFFCFF391B8C85EDB391" box="[160,185,385,410]" name="St" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">St</location>
. Thomas cruising shaded, calm pools on ghuts and ponds. 
<materialsCitation id="58973C34FF80FFFCFCD71B8C8645B3B6" collectorName="Only" location="Water Island" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" specimenCount="1">
<collectorName id="450A53BFFF80FFFCFCD71B8C86D6B391" box="[846,898,385,410]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">Only</collectorName>
once was it associated with an ornamental pond, and that was on 
<location id="ED2060B2FF80FFFCFD1D1BA98645B3B6" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:6056877FFF80FFFCFE5D1B2486F0B02E:ED2060B2FF80FFFCFD1D1BA98645B3B6" box="[644,785,420,445]" name="Water Island" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">Water Island</location>
</materialsCitation>
. At all locations, there was ample tree cover, and a partially closed canopy. 
<materialsCitation id="58973C34FF80FFFCFDED1BCB8788B009" location="Turpentine Run" municipality="St" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" specimenCount="1">
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF80FFFCFDED1BCB8672B3D4" author="Donnelly N" box="[628,806,454,479]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" pagination="7 - 9" refId="ref24517" refString="Donnelly N. 2002. Odonata of St. Thomas and St. John, Virgin Islands. Argia. 14 (1): 7 - 9." type="journal article" year="2002">Donnelly (2002)</bibRefCitation>
gives a similar habitat description and reports it from 
<location id="ED2060B2FF80FFFCFE371BE48708B009" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:6056877FFF80FFFCFE5D1B2486F0B02E:ED2060B2FF80FFFCFE371BE48708B009" box="[430,604,489,514]" municipality="St" name="Turpentine Run" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">Turpentine Run</location>
ghut on 
<collectingMunicipality id="0824AC13FF80FFFCFD5A1BE48788B009" box="[707,732,489,514]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">St</collectingMunicipality>
</materialsCitation>
. Thomas and from Lâ€™Esperance spring on 
<collectingRegion id="2A3BF88BFF80FFFCFF5C18018475B02E" box="[197,289,524,549]" country="United States Virgin Islands" name="Saint John" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">St. John</collectingRegion>
. We found nymphs in aquatic plants at 14 different sites.
</paragraph>
